docs.abstract: New data for 2018’s fourth quarter shows the British economy growing at its slowest pace since 2012, bringing the broad impact of a no-deal split from the European Union into sharp relief.
docs.snippet: New data for 2018’s fourth quarter shows the British economy growing at its slowest pace since 2012, bringing the broad impact of a no-deal split from the European Union into sharp relief.
docs.lead_paragraph: AMSTERDAM — If anyone in the Netherlands is happy about Britain jilting the European Union, they keep that sentiment to themselves. The country has been built on trade, with huge volumes of goods flowing from its ports across the English Channel. Brexit, as the divorce is known, has proved disruptive.

headline.main: U.K. Economy Falters as Brexit Looms. Amsterdam Sees Risks, and Opportunity.
headline.print_headline: As Clouds Loom for No-Deal Brexit, Amsterdam Sees Silver Lining

docs.lead_paragraph: QUITO, Ecuador — The squat gray building in Ecuador’s capital commands a sweeping view of the city’s sparkling sprawl, from the high-rises at the base of the Andean valley to the pastel neighborhoods that spill up its mountainsides.

headline.main: Made in China, Exported to the World: The Surveillance State

docs.abstract: New Jersey has the best, Illinois the worst, and far too many fail consumers, according to a study from the Center for Auto Safety.
docs.snippet: New Jersey has the best, Illinois the worst, and far too many fail consumers, according to a study from the Center for Auto Safety.
docs.lead_paragraph: Motorists who live in New Jersey and have a major problem with a new vehicle have a handy tool: the best lemon law in the land. But about a third of the states have such weak lemon laws that consumers will have a tough time getting a fair deal, according to a study released this month by the Center for Auto Safety.

headline.main: For Car Buyers Who Got a Lemon, State Laws Vary Widely
headline.print_headline: Strength of Lemon Laws In States Varies Widely

docs.abstract: A December essay for Vice was titled “My Bikini Audition From Hell Shows How Little Hollywood Has Changed.” It turns out it was about a Super Bowl ad.
docs.snippet: A December essay for Vice was titled “My Bikini Audition From Hell Shows How Little Hollywood Has Changed.” It turns out it was about a Super Bowl ad.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the first quarter of the Super Bowl on Sunday, in front of nearly 100 million viewers watching on CBS, Anheuser-Busch ran a commercial for its Bon & Viv hard seltzer brand. Two women, clad in cropped short-sleeved collared shirts, played the mythical mermaid founders of the brand and pitched the beverage to a group of talking sharks under the sea.

headline.main: A Super Bowl Mermaid Ad and a Sexist Audition
headline.print_headline: Seltzer Ad Is Accused Of Sexism In Essay

docs.abstract: If American Media is found to have broken a law, it would be in violation of a deal struck with federal prosecutors in connection to hush money paid to protect Donald Trump.
docs.snippet: If American Media is found to have broken a law, it would be in violation of a deal struck with federal prosecutors in connection to hush money paid to protect Donald Trump.
docs.lead_paragraph: Jeff Bezos, the founder of Amazon and the owner of The Washington Post, did not become the world’s richest man by refusing to do what it takes to win. And now that he finds himself in a mud fight with the supermarket tabloid that exposed his extramarital affair, he is showing off the same drive that helped him turn a simple idea — selling books on the internet — into an all-purpose, $780 billion powerhouse.

headline.main: Jeff Bezos’ Extortion Claim Said to Be Under Review by Prosecutors
headline.print_headline: U.S. Is Said to Look at Bezos’ Extortion Claim
